1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 1st Session of the 60th Legislature (2025)
3 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
FOR
5
6
7 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
8 An Act relating to the Oklahoma Open Meeting Act;
allowing members of a public body to participate in a
9 meeting from their private residence under certain
circumstances; excluding private residences from
10 location disclosure under certain circumstances;
clarifying applicability; defining term; clarifying
11 compliance requirements; stating legislative intent;
providing for codification; and providing an
12 effective date.
13
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
17 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 307.2 of Title 25, unless there
18 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
19 A. A member of a public body may participate in a public
20 meeting via videoconference or teleconference from the private
21 residence of the member, and shall not be required to disclose the
22 address of the private residence on the meeting notice or agenda,
23 provided the following conditions are met:
24
Req. No. 12931 Page 1
1 1. The member identifies the location as the "private
2 residence" on the meeting notice and agenda, without further detail;
3 2. The videoconference or teleconference technology used allows
4 the public to see and hear the member during the meeting; and
5 3. The member's participation from his or her private residence
6 does not restrict or limit public access to the meeting or the
7 member's contributions to the meeting.
8 B. This section does not apply when a public body holds a
9 meeting entirely or primarily at a member's private residence, or
10 when two or more members are present at a member's private
11 residence. In such cases, full disclosure of the meeting location
12 is required under the existing provisions of the Oklahoma Open
13 Meeting Act.
14 C. For purposes of this section, "private residence" means any
15 home, apartment, or other personal living space that is not used as
16 a public or commercial meeting site.
17 D. Public bodies shall ensure compliance with all other
18 provisions of the Oklahoma Open Meeting Act, including transparency,
19 accessibility, and notice requirements, when implementing this
20 section.
21 E. It is the Legislature's intent to balance the principles of
22 open governance with the privacy and security of individuals
23 participating in public meetings from private residences. This
24
Req. No. 12931 Page 2
1 sect ion ensures compliance with transparency requirements while
2 protecting personal addresses from public disclosure.
3 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
